<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,151,391]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,333,224,248]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named for Joshua, R. Jones, Department of Entomology, 
<collectingRegion box="[1151,1216,224,247]" country="United States of America" name="Texas" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Texas</collectingRegion>
A &amp; M University, College Station for his fine studies on the leafhopper subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[867,970,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Ledrinae">Ledrinae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="48.[151,1436,151,391]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,296,320]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Nielson, 1992: 300)" baseAuthorityName="Nielson" baseAuthorityPageNumber="300" baseAuthorityYear="1992" box="[604,976,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Docalidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="filamenta">
<emphasis box="[604,744,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">D. filamenta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Nielson" box="[758,968,295,319]" firstAuthor="Nielson" page="300" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" pagination="297 - 305" refId="ref55534" refString="Nielson, M. W. (1992 f) New species of Neotropical leafhoppers in the tribe Teruliini with a revised key to some species (Homoptera: Cicadellidae: Coelidiinae). Entomologica Scandinavica, 23 (3), 297 - 305." type="journal article" year="1992">Nielson, 1992:300</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
in stylar configuration and can be distinguished by the presence of aedeagal ventral process, configuration of base of aedeagal shaft which is triangulate in ventral view and by the processes on the distal half of the style which are spinate rather than setate.
</paragraph>
